        "text": "“Problem Solving with Pastoralists in Africa” \nProduced by Pamela McLean\n\nThis is the first of two shows about the importance of being heard and how community radio can help.  \n\nIt is a lively, practical show. The contributors have unusual stories to tell, and the ability to tell them in compelling ways. They.have a great depth of knowledge, see the topic from different perspectives, and are talking about things they are deeply committed to. The starting point is a conflict between farmers and pastoralists, and how local radio has been used for good (and sometimes for ill) in such situations. Then the topic widers out.\n\nWe look at:\nThe current pastoralist-farmer violence in South Kaduna\nWider perspective of pastoralist-farmer conflict in Nigeria\nSituation with pastoralists in Ethiopia\nDevelopment of community radio in those areas, especially related to pastoralists and farmers.\nKenyan experience of community radio and other communication technologies used  with farmers by three successive generations of community development workers .\nFEASTfm’s work with these communities. How it is breaking down barriers to communication and making the technology of radio production accessible, and affordable, thus enabling previously unheard voices to be included in global debates.  \n\nThere is a podcast setting the scene, followed by a studio discussion, and a call to action. The call to action gives students ways to get involved in the issues mentioned during the show, including contributing podcasts of what they are doing. The results of the call to action will be fed back into the second show.  \n\nThe contributors are:\n\nJohn Dada - Director of Fantsuam Foundation,working for twenty years in an area with a long history of sectarian violence - political/religious/tribal. Armed violence broke out again at Christmas and the area remains under curfew..\n\nChief Gbade Adejumo - On retiring from a career in state and local government he obtained a research based higher degree on pastoralist-farmer conflict in Nigeria.\n\nElfneh Bariso, Founder of AHEAD (Action for Health Education and Development) based in London, and leading AHEAD’s work in London and Ethiopia. Elfneh comes from a pastoralist community, and herded cattle as a boy. He came to London to study and gained a PhD at the Institute of Education.\n\nDavid Nzainga Mutua, the third generation of his family to be involved in community development in Kangundo in Kenya. They have always been innovators, making the most of the latest “communication technologies” to support their communities in sustainable ways.  In David’s case the technologies are radio, smart phones and internet. \n\nDavid Bovill Founder and Director of FEASTfm. David explains the connection between FEASTfm, SOAS and Kafanchan radio for this show and the one to follow.  He puts it in the context of the longer term development of FEASTfm\n"
